<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148D22DBAAB0B4E4FC" authorityName="Oldroyd" authorityYear="1968" box="[1121,1205,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Entesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148D22DBAAB0B4E4FC" box="[1121,1205,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Entesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group (
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148C1DDBAAB19DE4FC" box="[1374,1436,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFEAEFE8B370F61489D4DB8DB592E497" author="Winterton, S. L. &amp; Hardy, N. B. &amp; Gaimari, S. D. &amp; Hauser, M. &amp; Hill, H. N. &amp; Holston, K. C. &amp; Irwin, M. E. &amp; Lambkin, C. L. &amp; Metz, M. A. &amp; Turco, F. &amp; Webb, D. &amp; Yang, L. &amp; Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M." box="[151,403,189,216]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" pagination="144 - 161" refId="ref5854" refString="Winterton, S. L., Hardy, N. B., Gaimari, S. D., Hauser, M., Hill, H. N., Holston, K. C., Irwin, M. E., Lambkin, C. L., Metz, M. A., Turco, F., Webb, D., Yang, L., Yeates, D. K. &amp; Wiegmann, B. M. (2016) The phylogeny of stiletto flies (Diptera: Therevidae). Systematic Entomology, 41, 144 - 161. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12147" type="journal article" year="2016">
Winterton 
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F614884CDB8EB540E498" box="[271,321,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">et al</emphasis>
., 2016
</bibRefCitation>
), which also includes this new genus. We consider 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148A94DB8DB056E498" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[983,1111,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sigalopella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148A94DB8DB056E498" box="[983,1111,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Sigalopella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23CF370B370F6148D1CDB8DB0AAE498" box="[1119,1195,189,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
as the likely sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F61489D4DBD1B520E4B4" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1865" box="[151,289,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Pachyrrhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F61489D4DBD1B520E4B4" box="[151,289,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Pachyrrhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Amongst the South American 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148B3ADBD1B726E4B4" box="[633,807,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Agapophytinae">Agapophytinae</taxonomicName>
, these two genera share characteristics such as a protruding rounded parafacial with parafacial setae present, and the male post-ocular setae elongate and arranged in a single row dorsally. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F614886DDA19B5AFE50C" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[302,430,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sigalopella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F614886DDA19B5AFE50C" box="[302,430,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Sigalopella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23CF370B370F61488F7DA19B5FFE50C" box="[436,510,297,323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily recognised by the overall black coloration, narrow elongate antennae, absence of setal pile on the prosternum and incrassate palpi. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148A02DA7DB7CAE528" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1865" box="[833,971,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Pachyrrhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148A02DA7DB7CAE528" box="[833,971,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Pachyrrhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a notably short and bulbous antennal scape (
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F61489ABDA41B4FDE5C4" box="[232,252,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">cf</emphasis>
. elongate and narrow in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148B5EDA41B69CE5C4" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[541,669,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sigalopella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148B5EDA41B69CE5C4" box="[541,669,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Sigalopella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23CF370B370F6148BE5DA41B6F5E5C4" box="[678,756,369,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) and an abundance of macrosetae on the head and scutum. Most 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F614899ADAA5B562E5E0" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1865" box="[217,355,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Pachyrrhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F614899ADAA5B562E5E0" box="[217,355,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Pachyrrhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have mottled or hyaline wings, never uniformly infuscate like in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F6148D08DAA5B0CAE5E0" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[1099,1227,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sigalopella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F6148D08DAA5B0CAE5E0" box="[1099,1227,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Sigalopella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23CF370B370F6148D90DAA5B11EE5E0" box="[1235,1311,405,431]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7BE99AB370F61489D4DA89B516E59C" authority="Irwin &amp; Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[151,279,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sigalopella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B90F4E0BB370F61489D4DA89B516E59C" box="[151,279,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="278">Sigalopella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23CF370B370F614885CDA89B56DE59C" box="[287,364,441,467]" pageId="2" pageNumber="278" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are easily separated from each other using external characters such as colour and vestiture, as well as head and antennal shape; male and female genitalia is remarkably uniform amongst all members of the genus and is not useful for differentiating species in either sex.
</paragraph>
